Chartwells will be offering 5-day meal packages for breakfast and lunch this Thursday, 9/10 from 9:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. at Ethel McKnight Elementary School and Grace N. Rogers Elementary School. These meals are FREE to all children 18 years and younger.

Please enter in the side door at Ethel McKnight Elementary School and the rear entrance at Grace N. Rogers Elementary School. Students and families must wear a mask when picking up items.

Moving forward, 5-day meal packages will be offered every Tuesday from 9:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. at Ethel McKnight Elementary School and Grace N. Rogers Elementary School.

Dear EWRSD Community:

I hope this communication finds you and your families in good health.

This update serves as a follow up to the Board of Education meeting that took place on Monday, August 24, 2020. During the meeting, I asked the Board to approve an addendum to the EWRSD Restart and Recovery Plan that was originally approved on August 3, 2020. The addendum included the following recommendation for the 2020-21 school year:

- Begin remotely for all students on Wednesday, September 9, 2020.
- Begin in-person instruction on Monday, November 9, 2020.

Read more here: https://bit.ly/2WxkrYg.

post_text:
The candidates for the East Windsor Regional School District Board Of Education 2020 Election have been announced by the Mercer County Clerk‚Äôs Office.

Three candidates will run for one full three-year term representing East Windsor Township on the East Windsor Regional School District Board of Education.

The candidates are incumbent school board members Jeanne Marlene Bourjolly and Robert P. Laverty as well as Jagruti Patel.

No one has filed to run for a one-year unexpired term on the school board to represent East Windsor.

No one has filed to run for a full, three-year term on the school board to represent Hightstown Borough.

Election Day is November 3, 2020. For more information on how to register to vote and to vote by mail, visit http://www.mercercounty.org/boards-commissions/board-of-elections. If you are unsure if you have previously registered to vote, visit https://bit.ly/2KgsdQ6.

post_text:
Congratulations to Hightstown High School junior, Katie Scheid for her first-place win overall and a gold medal at the virtual state competition for Family, Career and Community Leaders of America in Sports Nutrition.

For this project, Ms. Scheid created a nutrition and hydration plan in order to meet the nutritional needs of a competitive student-athlete. She then had to analyze the plan she devised and create a display board and presentation. The project was titled ‚ÄúSwing for the Fences with Healthy Eating‚Äù because she chose to model the project after her cousin, Sam, who is currently on the softball team at Rowan University in New Jersey.

Ms. Scheid qualified to compete at nationals in early June and will be representing HHS in the Sports Nutrition event.

We wish you all the best!

Remote Learning will resume on Wednesday, May 27, 2020.

This serves as a brief update regarding Remote Learning within the East Windsor Regional School District. It was approximately a month ago when our buildings were last filled with students and staff. Since that time, a significant amount of change has occurred as we transitioned to the process of bridging the learning process while students are at home. During this time, our very talented teachers have been working diligently to creatively address the needs of our students. Throughout this new experience, I will continue to express my gratitude to our students, teachers, and families, as we adjust to this temporary mode of learning.

Read more here: https://bit.ly/2Kjnaz8.

Have you responded to the 2020 Census yet?

Respond today ‚Äî online, by phone, or by mail ‚Äî and count every person living in your home, including all children.

When everyone is counted, our community receives the funding we need for schools, health care, jobs, roads, emergency services, housing and food assistance, programs for children and seniors, and much more.

Your responses are confidential and cannot be used against you in any way.

FILL IT OUT at 2020Census.gov or 844-330-2020 (English) / 844-468-2020 (Spanish).

post_text:
You still have time to submit lottery applications and contracts for the 2020-2021 Integrated Preschool lottery!

Currently, the Central Registration Office is closed to the public. Two bins are available outside the office with the Integrated Preschool Applications. Our address is 384 Stockton Street, Hightstown. You can also find the application here: https://bit.ly/2UlxFYh.

We are accepting materials in our dropbox through the mail slot on our door as well as electronically via centralregistration@ewrsd.k12.nj.us or via Fax: 609-443-7855.

If you drop materials off, please provide copies. If originals are dropped off, they will be copied and the originals will be mailed to the home. Please call the below number to alert us that materials were dropped off. We will then reply with your ticket number and also mail the stub out to you.

Any questions, please call the Central Registration Office at 609-443-2881, Ext. 6800

Lottery applications must be returned or emailed to the Central Registration Building no later than 12:00 p.m. Tuesday, March 31, 2020.

In an effort to preserve the health and well-being of the members of the East Windsor Regional School District, the current public health-related school closure will be extended for at least an additional week. Therefore, the district will continue remote learning from March 30 through April 5, 2020.

The school district is already scheduled to be closed for spring break from April 6 through April 12, 2020. The proposed date to reopen the East Windsor Regional Schools will now be Monday, April 13, 2020. This new date is subject to change.

Read more here: https://bit.ly/2QEm5VT.

Happy Birthday, Dr. Seuss! We cannot wait to share all the fun we are having in our schools for Read Across America week.

Reader's Oath
By Debra Angstead, Missouri-NEA

I promise to read
Each day and each night.
I know it‚Äôs the key
To growing up right.

I‚Äôll read to myself,
I‚Äôll read to a crowd.
It makes no difference
If silent or loud.

I‚Äôll read at my desk,
At home and at school,
On my bean bag or bed,
By the fire or pool.

Each book that I read
Puts smarts in my head,
‚ÄôCause brains grow more thoughts
The more they are fed.

So I take this oath
To make reading my way
Of feeding my brain
What it needs every day.

post_text:
Students have been busy engineers in the Perry L. Drew Elementary School STEM Lab.

From designing prototypes of carnival games to designing pinball games - they are ready to become game designers.

Students also helped Rapunzel find an alternative to using her hair to get down the tower.

Finally, they celebrated the 100th day of school by constructing and building by following the criteria of needing 100 manipulatives.

#STEM4them

post_text:
Congratulations to the Hightstown High School Wrestling Team for placing second as a team in the District 23 Tournament.

Our team broke a school record by sending nine wrestlers to the Region 6 tournament which begins on Wednesday.

Kether Thornton and Brenden Hansen both took first place in their weight classes.

Alex and Chris Stavrou and Elijah Rodriguez all placed second and Robert Fattore, Joe Obst, Gio Morina and Bryan Bonilla all placed third to move on to Regions.

Seniors Tyree Doss and Nico Leaver both took fourth place.
